        <fr:title text="Context">Context</fr:title>
      </fr:frontmatter>
      <fr:mainmatter>
        <fr:tree show-metadata="true" expanded="false" toc="false" numbered="false">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:authors>
              <fr:author>
                <fr:link href="/lectures/ellieripley/" title="Ellie Ripley" uri="https://negation.rocks/lectures/ellieripley/" display-uri="ellieripley" type="local">Ellie Ripley</fr:link>
              </fr:author>
            </fr:authors>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2026</fr:year>
              <fr:month>5</fr:month>
              <fr:day>16</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:uri>https://negation.rocks/lectures/009C/</fr:uri>
            <fr:display-uri>009C</fr:display-uri>
            <fr:route>/lectures/009C/</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Expansion">Expansion</fr:title>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <html:p>Expansion is the flipside of reduction.
We use reductions to argue that, given our introduction rules, our elimination rules don't give us <html:em>too much</html:em>, don't allow us to reach conclusions via local peaks that we couldn't reach otherwise.
On the other hand, expansions show that, given our introduction rules, our elimination rules give us <html:em>enough</html:em>: we don't <html:em>lose</html:em> information by using our rules.</html:p>
            <html:p>The idea here is that, from assuming a compound sentence and applying its elimination rule(s), we should be able to arrive directly at enough to be able to introduce that very compound sentence again.</html:p>
            <html:p>Think again about tonk: it doesn't give us expansions either.
From an assumption of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A \# B]]></fr:tex>, we can eliminate the tonk to arrive at <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[B]]></fr:tex>.
But we can't use <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\#]]></fr:tex> I from <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[B]]></fr:tex> to arrive back at <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A \# B]]></fr:tex>; we would need to have an <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> to do that.</html:p>
            <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:authors>
                  <fr:author>
                    <fr:link href="/lectures/ellieripley/" title="Ellie Ripley" uri="https://negation.rocks/lectures/ellieripley/" display-uri="ellieripley" type="local">Ellie Ripley</fr:link>
                  </fr:author>
                </fr:authors>
                <fr:date>
                  <fr:year>2026</fr:year>
                  <fr:month>5</fr:month>
                  <fr:day>16</fr:day>
                </fr:date>
                <fr:uri>https://negation.rocks/lectures/009D/</fr:uri>
                <fr:display-uri>009D</fr:display-uri>
                <fr:route>/lectures/009D/</fr:route>
                <fr:taxon>Side note</fr:taxon>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <html:p>What about this proof?</html:p>
                <html:p>
                  <fr:resource hash="7f34955845a6fe9f36f6017de574a716">
                    <fr:resource-content>
                      <html:img src="/lectures/7f34955845a6fe9f36f6017de574a716.svg" />
                    </fr:resource-content>
                    <fr:resource-source type="latex" part="preamble"><![CDATA[
  \usepackage {bussproofs}
  \newcommand {\DP }{\DisplayProof }
  ]]></fr:resource-source>
                    <fr:resource-source type="latex" part="body"><![CDATA[
\AxiomC{\ensuremath{A \# B\vphantom{|}}}
\LeftLabel{\ensuremath{\scriptsize  \# E\quad }}
\UnaryInfC{\ensuremath{B\vphantom{|}}}
\LeftLabel{\ensuremath{\scriptsize  \# I\quad }}
\UnaryInfC{\ensuremath{B \# A\vphantom{|}}}
\LeftLabel{\ensuremath{\scriptsize  \# E\quad }}
\UnaryInfC{\ensuremath{A\vphantom{|}}}
\LeftLabel{\ensuremath{\scriptsize  \# I\quad }}
\UnaryInfC{\ensuremath{A \# B\vphantom{|}}}
\DP
]]></fr:resource-source>
                  </fr:resource>
                </html:p>
                <html:p>Doesn't that show that by assuming <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A \# B]]></fr:tex> and applying the elimination rule, we can get enough to be able to reintroduce <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A \# B]]></fr:tex>?</html:p>
                <html:p>Well, not in the sense we're aiming for with expansion.
The key is in noting that this isn't <html:em>direct</html:em>; we had to exploit tonk's other non-reducing funny business to be able to pull this off.</html:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
            </fr:tree>
            <html:p>However, once again tonk is the outlier; we can show expansion for our other connectives.</html:p>
            <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:authors>
                  <fr:author>
                    <fr:link href="/lectures/ellieripley/" title="Ellie Ripley" uri="https://negation.rocks/lectures/ellieripley/" display-uri="ellieripley" type="local">Ellie Ripley</fr:link>
                  </fr:author>
                </fr:authors>
                <fr:date>
                  <fr:year>2026</fr:year>
                  <fr:month>5</fr:month>
                  <fr:day>16</fr:day>
                </fr:date>
                <fr:uri>https://negation.rocks/lectures/009E/</fr:uri>
                <fr:display-uri>009E</fr:display-uri>
                <fr:route>/lectures/009E/</fr:route>
                <fr:title text="Expansion for conjunction">Expansion for conjunction</fr:title>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <html:p>Here is expansion for conjunction:</html:p>
                <html:p>
                  <fr:resource hash="fe54319d7b60ac9580dc07168059ac6d">
                    <fr:resource-content>
                      <html:img src="/lectures/fe54319d7b60ac9580dc07168059ac6d.svg" />
                    </fr:resource-content>
                    <fr:resource-source type="latex" part="preamble"><![CDATA[
  \usepackage {bussproofs}
  \newcommand {\DP }{\DisplayProof }
  ]]></fr:resource-source>
                    <fr:resource-source type="latex" part="body"><![CDATA[
\AxiomC{\ensuremath{A \land  B\vphantom{|}}}
\LeftLabel{\ensuremath{\scriptsize  \land  E_l\quad }}
\UnaryInfC{\ensuremath{A\vphantom{|}}}
\AxiomC{\ensuremath{A \land  B\vphantom{|}}}
\LeftLabel{\ensuremath{\scriptsize  \land  E_l\quad }}
\UnaryInfC{\ensuremath{B\vphantom{|}}}
\LeftLabel{\ensuremath{\scriptsize  \land  I\quad }}
\BinaryInfC{\ensuremath{A \land  B\vphantom{|}}}
\DP
]]></fr:resource-source>
                  </fr:resource>
                </html:p>
                <html:p>By assuming <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A \land  B]]></fr:tex> and applying both elimination rules to it, we immediately arrive at just what we need to be able to apply the introduction rule, returning to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A \land  B]]></fr:tex>.
This shows that in a sense nothing is lost when we introduce a conjunction: we can always eliminate it again to get back everything we put in.</html:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:authors>
                  <fr:author>
                    <fr:link href="/lectures/ellieripley/" title="Ellie Ripley" uri="https://negation.rocks/lectures/ellieripley/" display-uri="ellieripley" type="local">Ellie Ripley</fr:link>
                  </fr:author>
                </fr:authors>
                <fr:date>
                  <fr:year>2026</fr:year>
                  <fr:month>5</fr:month>
                  <fr:day>16</fr:day>
                </fr:date>
                <fr:uri>https://negation.rocks/lectures/009F/</fr:uri>
                <fr:display-uri>009F</fr:display-uri>
                <fr:route>/lectures/009F/</fr:route>
                <fr:title text="Expansion for implication">Expansion for implication</fr:title>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <html:p>Let's take a look now at expansion for implication:</html:p>
                <html:p>
                  <fr:resource hash="0d38992d1497608151e7839e9d20049e">
                    <fr:resource-content>
                      <html:img src="/lectures/0d38992d1497608151e7839e9d20049e.svg" />
                    </fr:resource-content>
                    <fr:resource-source type="latex" part="preamble"><![CDATA[
  \usepackage {bussproofs}
  \newcommand {\DP }{\DisplayProof }
  ]]></fr:resource-source>
                    <fr:resource-source type="latex" part="body"><![CDATA[
\AxiomC{\ensuremath{A \rightarrow  B\vphantom{|}}}
\AxiomC{\ensuremath{[A]^9\vphantom{|}}}
\LeftLabel{\ensuremath{\scriptsize  \rightarrow  E\quad }}
\BinaryInfC{\ensuremath{B\vphantom{|}}}
\LeftLabel{\ensuremath{\scriptsize  \rightarrow  I^9\quad }}
\UnaryInfC{\ensuremath{A \rightarrow  B\vphantom{|}}}
\DP
]]></fr:resource-source>
                  </fr:resource>
                </html:p>
                <html:p>Note that here we needed to assume something extra to be able to eliminate <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A \rightarrow  B]]></fr:tex> at all.
But that extra assumption is taken care of directly by the introduction rule; this is a clean balance indeed!</html:p>
                <html:p>You can see the introduction rule for implication as saying that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A \rightarrow  B]]></fr:tex> packages up a proof of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[B]]></fr:tex> from <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex>.
The expansion step shows that you can unpackage this implication to get exactly that.</html:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:authors>
                  <fr:author>
                    <fr:link href="/lectures/ellieripley/" title="Ellie Ripley" uri="https://negation.rocks/lectures/ellieripley/" display-uri="ellieripley" type="local">Ellie Ripley</fr:link>
                  </fr:author>
                </fr:authors>
                <fr:date>
                  <fr:year>2026</fr:year>
                  <fr:month>5</fr:month>
                  <fr:day>16</fr:day>
                </fr:date>
                <fr:uri>https://negation.rocks/lectures/009G/</fr:uri>
                <fr:display-uri>009G</fr:display-uri>
                <fr:route>/lectures/009G/</fr:route>
                <fr:title text="Expansion for disjunction">Expansion for disjunction</fr:title>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <html:p>Here is expansion for disjunction:</html:p>
                <html:p>
                  <fr:resource hash="8af47ad7ca40f12da03d396c94eecabd">
                    <fr:resource-content>
                      <html:img src="/lectures/8af47ad7ca40f12da03d396c94eecabd.svg" />
                    </fr:resource-content>
                    <fr:resource-source type="latex" part="preamble"><![CDATA[
  \usepackage {bussproofs}
  \newcommand {\DP }{\DisplayProof }
  ]]></fr:resource-source>
                    <fr:resource-source type="latex" part="body"><![CDATA[
\AxiomC{\ensuremath{A \lor  B\vphantom{|}}}
\AxiomC{\ensuremath{[A]^3\vphantom{|}}}
\LeftLabel{\ensuremath{\scriptsize  \lor  I_l\quad }}
\UnaryInfC{\ensuremath{A \lor  B\vphantom{|}}}
\AxiomC{\ensuremath{[B]^3\vphantom{|}}}
\LeftLabel{\ensuremath{\scriptsize  \lor  I_r\quad }}
\UnaryInfC{\ensuremath{A \lor  B\vphantom{|}}}
\LeftLabel{\ensuremath{\scriptsize  \lor  E^3\quad }}
\TrinaryInfC{\ensuremath{A \lor  B\vphantom{|}}}
\DP
]]></fr:resource-source>
                  </fr:resource>
                </html:p>
                <html:p>Here, we can see that eliminating <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A \lor  B]]></fr:tex> gives us just enough to, by using both introduction rules in the appropriate way, get it back.</html:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:authors>
                  <fr:author>
                    <fr:link href="/lectures/ellieripley/" title="Ellie Ripley" uri="https://negation.rocks/lectures/ellieripley/" display-uri="ellieripley" type="local">Ellie Ripley</fr:link>
                  </fr:author>
                </fr:authors>
                <fr:date>
                  <fr:year>2026</fr:year>
                  <fr:month>5</fr:month>
                  <fr:day>16</fr:day>
                </fr:date>
                <fr:uri>https://negation.rocks/lectures/009H/</fr:uri>
                <fr:display-uri>009H</fr:display-uri>
                <fr:route>/lectures/009H/</fr:route>
                <fr:title text="Expansion for negation">Expansion for negation</fr:title>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <html:p>As with their reductions, expansion for negation is very like expansion for implication:</html:p>
                <html:p>
                  <fr:resource hash="818eccef5794ffe83a99dec7b106393f">
                    <fr:resource-content>
                      <html:img src="/lectures/818eccef5794ffe83a99dec7b106393f.svg" />
                    </fr:resource-content>
                    <fr:resource-source type="latex" part="preamble"><![CDATA[
  \usepackage {bussproofs}
  \newcommand {\DP }{\DisplayProof }
  ]]></fr:resource-source>
                    <fr:resource-source type="latex" part="body"><![CDATA[
\AxiomC{\ensuremath{\neg  A\vphantom{|}}}
\AxiomC{\ensuremath{[A]^2\vphantom{|}}}
\LeftLabel{\ensuremath{\scriptsize  \neg  E\quad }}
\BinaryInfC{\ensuremath{\bot \vphantom{|}}}
\LeftLabel{\ensuremath{\scriptsize  \neg  I^2\quad }}
\UnaryInfC{\ensuremath{\neg  A\vphantom{|}}}
\DP
]]></fr:resource-source>
                  </fr:resource>
                </html:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:authors>
                  <fr:author>
                    <fr:link href="/lectures/ellieripley/" title="Ellie Ripley" uri="https://negation.rocks/lectures/ellieripley/" display-uri="ellieripley" type="local">Ellie Ripley</fr:link>
                  </fr:author>
                </fr:authors>
                <fr:date>
                  <fr:year>2026</fr:year>
                  <fr:month>5</fr:month>
                  <fr:day>16</fr:day>
                </fr:date>
                <fr:uri>https://negation.rocks/lectures/009I/</fr:uri>
                <fr:display-uri>009I</fr:display-uri>
                <fr:route>/lectures/009I/</fr:route>
                <fr:title text="Expansion for verum and falsum">Expansion for verum and falsum</fr:title>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <html:p>For verum and falsum, there are two ways to look at it.
You might think that, since verum has no elimination rules and falsum no introduction rules, there is nothing to show here, so we're all set.
That was the situation with reduction, after all.</html:p>
                <html:p>I do think there's something to be said for that way of thinking.
But we can also think of things another way.</html:p>
                <html:p>For verum, we might note that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\top  I]]></fr:tex> tells us that we can conclude verum from <html:em>nothing at all</html:em>.
The fact that verum has no elimination rule, then, is indeed perfectly balanced with this.
The nothing that we get from verum via its (nonexistent) elimination rule is indeed exactly what it takes to introduce it.</html:p>
                <html:p>And for falsum, we can simply note the proof:</html:p>
                <html:p>
                  <fr:resource hash="34ac8827af93c388d8b8d56289fa87ce">
                    <fr:resource-content>
                      <html:img src="/lectures/34ac8827af93c388d8b8d56289fa87ce.svg" />
                    </fr:resource-content>
                    <fr:resource-source type="latex" part="preamble"><![CDATA[
  \usepackage {bussproofs}
  \newcommand {\DP }{\DisplayProof }
  ]]></fr:resource-source>
                    <fr:resource-source type="latex" part="body"><![CDATA[
\AxiomC{\ensuremath{\bot \vphantom{|}}}
\LeftLabel{\ensuremath{\scriptsize  \bot  E\quad }}
\UnaryInfC{\ensuremath{\bot \vphantom{|}}}
\DP]]></fr:resource-source>
                  </fr:resource>
                </html:p>
                <html:p>This shows that by eliminating falsum we get enough to conclude falsum, using all of its (zero) introduction rules.</html:p>
                <html:p>Either way we think about things, then, verum and falsum do obey expansion.</html:p>
                <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
                  <fr:frontmatter>
                    <fr:authors>
                      <fr:author>
                        <fr:link href="/lectures/ellieripley/" title="Ellie Ripley" uri="https://negation.rocks/lectures/ellieripley/" display-uri="ellieripley" type="local">Ellie Ripley</fr:link>
                      </fr:author>
                    </fr:authors>
                    <fr:date>
                      <fr:year>2026</fr:year>
                      <fr:month>5</fr:month>
                      <fr:day>16</fr:day>
                    </fr:date>
                    <fr:uri>https://negation.rocks/lectures/009J/</fr:uri>
                    <fr:display-uri>009J</fr:display-uri>
                    <fr:route>/lectures/009J/</fr:route>
                    <fr:taxon>Side note</fr:taxon>
                  </fr:frontmatter>
                  <fr:mainmatter>
                    <html:p>It might seem like not much hangs on the difference between those two ways of thinking, since verum and falsum both turn out to obey expansion either way.
But if we start to consider other possible connectives, we can see the difference.</html:p>
                    <html:p>Imagine a nullary connective <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[!]]></fr:tex>, for example, that has no introduction rules and the following elimination rule:</html:p>
                    <html:p>
                      <fr:resource hash="5ebdcc876731bf028c3d9a77198b53e7">
                        <fr:resource-content>
                          <html:img src="/lectures/5ebdcc876731bf028c3d9a77198b53e7.svg" />
                        </fr:resource-content>
                        <fr:resource-source type="latex" part="preamble"><![CDATA[
  \usepackage {bussproofs}
  \newcommand {\DP }{\DisplayProof }
  ]]></fr:resource-source>
                        <fr:resource-source type="latex" part="body"><![CDATA[
\AxiomC{\ensuremath{!\vphantom{|}}}
\LeftLabel{\ensuremath{\scriptsize  !E\quad }}
\UnaryInfC{\ensuremath{p\vphantom{|}}}
\DP
]]></fr:resource-source>
                      </fr:resource>
                    </html:p>
                    <html:p>Since this has no introduction rules, we can certainly handle reductions for it: no local peaks can ever arise.
But what about expansion?
Is its elimination rule really powerful enough to get everything we can get from <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[!]]></fr:tex>?
I'd be tempted to say no it isn't: since there's no way to prove <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[!]]></fr:tex> from <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p]]></fr:tex>, the elimination rule doesn't give us enough.</html:p>
                  </fr:mainmatter>
                </fr:tree>
              </fr:mainmatter>
            </fr:tree>
          </fr:mainmatter>
        </fr:tree>
      </fr:mainmatter>
    </fr:tree>
